rca 1149–circa 1190","1147–Female":"1147–Overleden","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1216–Male":"1216–Overleden","1102–Male":"1102–Overleden","1190":"1190","1216":"1216","1149":"1149","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","Abt 1149":"circa 1149","Abt 1190":"circa 1190","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1149–Abt 1190":"about 1149–about 1190","1147–Female":"1147–Deceased","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1216–Male":"1216–Deceased","1102–Male":"1102–Deceased","1190":"1190","1216":"1216","1149":"1149","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","Abt 1149":"about 1149","Abt 1190":"about 1190","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marsham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Marsham (Norfolk)."],"variants":[{"name":"Marshom","meanings":["English:  see  Marsham  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Marsham was born about 1149, in Marsham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Richard Marsham. He had at least 1 son. He died about 1190, at the age of 43."},"et":{"Abt 1149–Abt 1190":"umbes 1149–umbes 1190","1147–Female":"1147–Surnud","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1216–Male":"1216–Surnud","1102–Male":"1102–Surnud","1190":"1190","1216":"1216","1149":"1149","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","Abt 1149":"umbes 1149","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1149–Abt 1190":"noin 1149–noin 1190","1147–Female":"1147–Kuollut","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1216–Male":"1216–Kuollut","1102–Male":"1102–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1216":"1216","1149":"1149","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","Abt 1149":"noin 1149","Abt 1190":"noin 1190","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1149–Abt 1190":"environ 1149–environ 1190","1147–Female":"1147–Décédée","1149–1190":"1149–1190","1216–Male":"1216–Décédé","1102–Male":"1102–Décédé","1190":"1190","1216":"1216","1149":"1149","1147":"1147","1102":"1102","Abt 1149":"environ 1149","Abt 1190":"environ 1190","Of Marsham, Norfolk, England":"Marsham, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Richard Marsham est né environ 1149, à Marsham, Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Richard Marsham. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé environ 1190, à l’âge de 43 ans."},"de":{"Abt 1149–Abt 1190":"um